Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

The maximum number of times the contract can be renewed. column12:
Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. Set its `.description` according to the definition corresponding to the code in the [EU Main Activity concept-scheme](https://op.europa.eu/en/web/eu-vocabularies/concept-scheme/-/resource?uri=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/main-activity).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

The maximum number of times the contract can be renewed. By renewing, the buyer reserves the right (i.e. not an obligation) to renew the contract (i.e. extend its duration) without a new procurement procedure. For example, a contract may be valid for one year and the buyer may keep a possibility to renew it (e.g. once, twice) for another three months, if he is content with the services he received.

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

The maximum number of times the contract can be renewed. For example, a contract may be valid for one year and the buyer may keep a possibility to renew it (e.g. once, twice) for another three months, if he is content with the services he received.

column9: The brief description of criteria regarding the personal situation of tenderers that may lead to their exclusion. column9: The criteria (or criterion) of the given type are (is) used, unused, or (in case of prior information notice used as a call for competition or to reduce time limits) the use is not yet known.

column14: Concatenate it with BT-750 Selection Criteria Name.

column3: Selection Criteria Second Stage Invite Number
column9: A number linked to the selection criteria (or criterion).
column12: Add a Selection criterion object to the lot's `.selectionCriteria.criteria`. Map to its `.minimum`.

column3: Selection Criteria Second Stage Invite Number Weight
column9: Whether the number linked to a selection criterion (or selection criteria) is a type of weight (e.g. a percentage).

column3: Selection Criteria Second Stage Invite Number Threshold
column9: Whether the number linked to a selection criterion (or selection criteria) is a type of threshold (e.g. a minimum score, a maximum number of tenders with the highest score passing).

column12: [Create a new party](common-operations), map the code according to the [organisation role mapping table], and add it to the party's `.roles` array.

column9: An identifier of one or more sections within this notice. The information in the organisation section refers to this section or these sections.
column12: No guidance. Relationships are either implied by the XML structure or explicit via references from a section to the organization.

column9: The name of a part of an organisation (e.g. the relevant department of a large buyer).
column12: Append to the party's `.name`, separated from the original text with ' - ' (space, dash, space). column9: The official name of the organisation.

To avoid unnecessary processing of personal data, the contact point may allow the identification of a physical person only when necessary (in the sense of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and Regulation (EU) 2018/1725).

The telephone for contacting the organisation. To avoid unnecessary processing of personal data, the telephone may allow the identification of a physical person only when necessary (in the sense of the General Data Protection Regulation).

column12:
Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. Set its `.description` according to the definition corresponding to the code in the [EU Main Activity concept-scheme](https://op.europa.eu/en/web/eu-vocabularies/concept-scheme/-/resource?uri=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/main-activity).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

column9: The type of buyer according to procurement legislation (e.g. central government authority, body governed by public law, public undertaking).

column12:

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). column9: The official name of the organisation.
An identifier of the organisation. All of the organisation's identifiers shall be given.

The name of the department or other contact point for communicating with the organisation. To avoid unnecessary processing of personal data, the contact point may allow the identification of a physical person only when necessary (in the sense of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and Regulation (EU) 2018/1725).

The telephone for contacting the organisation. To avoid unnecessary processing of personal data, the telephone may allow the identification of a physical person only when necessary (in the sense of the General Data Protection Regulation).
The website of the organisation.
column14: Copied from the SF guidance but not imported automatically.

column9: The email for contacting the organisation. To avoid unnecessary processing of personal data, the email may allow the identification of a physical person only when necessary (in the sense of the General Data Protection Regulation).
The location according to the common classification of territorial units for statistics (NUTS) of the organisation's physical address. The NUTS3 classification code must be used.
column12: Map to the party's `.address.region`. There is an [open issue](https://github.com/open-contracting/standard/issues/739) about region codes.

column9: The organisation's uniform resource locator for exchange of data and documents.
The name of the street, road, avenue, etc., of the organisation's physical address and further identification (e.g. building number).
The post code of the organisation's physical address.
The name of the locality (city, town or village) of the organisation's physical address.
The country of the organisation's physical address.
column12: Translate to a country name, and map to the party's `.address.countryName`\n\nThere's an open issue ([#524](https://github.com/open-contracting/standard/issues/524)) to add a `.countryCode` field to the `Address` object, to avoid translation.

column9: The organisation is a natural person.
column12: Discard. There's an open issue ([#883](https://github.com/open-contracting/standard/issues/883)) to distinguish natural persons from organizations.

column9: The fax for contacting the organisation. To avoid unnecessary processing of personal data, the fax may allow the identification of a physical person only when necessary (in the sense of the General Data Protection Regulation).
The sub-role of the organisation in the procurement procedure (e.g. group leader, organisation providing additional information about the procurement procedure).
The main activity of the contracting authority.
column12:
Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. Set its `.description` according to the definition corresponding to the code in the [EU Main Activity concept-scheme](https://op.europa.eu/en/web/eu-vocabularies/concept-scheme/-/resource?uri=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/main-activity).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

column9: The type of buyer according to procurement legislation (e.g. central government authority, body governed by public law, public undertaking).
column12: Get the Organization object for the buyer, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array. Set the classification's `.scheme` to 'TED_CA_TYPE', map to its `.id` and set its `.description` according to the [official codelist](https://op.europa.eu/en/web/eu-vocabularies/concept-scheme/-/resource?uri=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/buyer-legal-type).

column9: The website where the buyer publishes information regarding procurement procedures (e.g. notices, procurement documents).
The main activity of the contracting entity.
column12:
Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. Set its `.description` according to the definition corresponding to the code in the [EU Main Activity code list](https://op.europa.eu/en/web/eu-vocabularies/concept-scheme/-/resource?uri=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/main-activity).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

column9: An identifier of one or more lots. The information in the reward and jury section refers to this lot or these lots.

The decision of the jury is binding on the buyer.

A name of the jury member.
column12: Add a `JuryMember` object to the lot's `.designContest.juryMembers` array, and map to its `.name`

column9: A name of an already selected participant. A participant could have been selected already at the time of the publication of the design contest notice because, for example, the information about the participation of a world renowned architect is intended to promote the contest amongst other potential participants.
column12: [Add a party](../../operations/#add-a-party), add 'selectedParticipant' to its `.roles`, and map to its `.name`. Add an `OrganizationReference` object to the lot's `.designContest.selectedParticipants` array, set its `.id` to the party's `.id`, and map to its `.name`.

column9: The place (e.g. first place, second place) in a design contest that receives the prize.
column12: Add a Prize object to the lot's `.designContest.prizes.details` array. Set its `.id`. The position of the prize object in the `.details` array determines the rank of the prize. Example: `.details[0]` should return the highest ranking prize, `.details[1]` the second highest ranking prize, etc.

column9: The value of the prize, if any, for the winner of the design contest.
column12: Map to the prize's `.value.amount`. Map `@currencyID` to the value's `.currency`.

column9: An identifier of one or more lots or one or more groups of lots. The information in the award criteria section refers to this lot, these lots, this group, or these groups.
column12: Refer to the [guidance for lot identifiers](common-operations lot identifier).

column9: The mathematical equation or any other description used for complicated weighing of criteria (e.g. non-linear weighing, the analytic hierarchy process) when a weighing cannot be expressed per criterion.
The justification for only indicating the award criteria's order of importance, not their weighing.
Whether the criterion concerns the price, the cost, or a non-price non-cost attribute of the tender. (Price is the acquisition price; cost is any other non-price monetary criterion.)
The description of the award criterion.
The name of the award criterion.
A number linked to an award criterion.
column12: Add an award criterion number to the award criterion's `.numbers` array. Map to its `.number`.

column9: Whether the number linked to an award criterion is a type of weight (e.g. a percentage).
column12: Map the code according to the [award criterion weight mapping table], and map it to the award criterion number's `.weight`.

column9: Whether the number linked to an award criterion is a fixed value (e.g. a fixed price, a fixed cost).
column12: Map the code according to the [award criterion fixed mapping table], and map it to the award criterion number's `.fixed`.

column9: Whether the number linked to an award criterion is a type of threshold (e.g. a minimum score, a maximum number of tenders with the highest score passing).
column12: Map the code according to the [award criterion threshold mapping table], and map it to the award criterion number's `.threshold`.

column9: An identifier of one or more lots. In case of PINs used only for information, the identifier of one or more parts of the notice that may later become lots or a self-standing procedures. column9: The name of the street, road, avenue, etc., of the place of performance and further identification (e.g. building number).

column9: The postcode of the place of performance.

column9: Additional information about the place of performance.

The unit which the good, service, or work comes in, for example hours or kilograms. Where CPV code is a supply which does not need a further unit (e.g. cars), then no unit needs to be given and quantity is taken to be a count, e.g. the "number of cars".
column12: Map to the item's `.unit.id`. column9: The estimated maximum value which can be spent in a framework agreement within a group of lots. Estimated refers to estimation at the time of launching the call for competition. Maximum value means a value covering all contracts to be awarded within a framework agreement over its whole duration, including options and renewals.

column12: Refer to the [guidance for lot identifiers](common-operations lot identifier).

column9: The duration is unknown, unlimited, etc.
Any other information about the renewal(s).

The maximum number of times the contract can be renewed. By renewing, the buyer reserves the right (i.e. not an obligation) to renew the contract (i.e. extend its duration) without a new procurement procedure. For example, a contract may be valid for one year and the buyer may keep a possibility to renew it (e.g. once, twice) for another three months, if he is content with the services he received.
The applicable law when buyers from different countries procure together within one procurement procedure.
The type of procurement procedure (e.g. according to the types given in the procurement Directives).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). The position of the cascade object in the `.cascade` array determines the rank of the bid. Example: `.cascade[0]` should return the highest ranking bid, `.cascade[1]` the second highest ranking bid, etc.

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

column9: The type of tenders or requests to participate received. The total number of tenders received must be given. When a notice does not fall under Directive 2009/81/EC and is not about social or other specific services, the number of tenders received from micro, small and medium enterprises; the number of tenders received from tenderers registered in other European Economic Area countries and the number of tenders received from tenderers registered in countries outside of the European Economic Area must also be given. All tenders must be counted, regardless of whether they are admissible or inadmissible. For tenders submitted by a group of tenderers (e.g. a consortium), the tender must be counted in the relevant category (e.g. SME) if the majority of the work is expected to be done by tenderers which fall within this category (e.g. they are SMEs).

The position of the cascade object in the `.cascade` array determines the rank of the bid. Example: `.cascade[0]` ought to return the highest ranking bid, `.cascade[1]` the second highest ranking bid, etc.

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

For tenders submitted by a group of tenderers (e.g. a consortium), the tender must be counted in the relevant category (e.g. SME) if the majority of the work is expected to be done by tenderers which fall within this category (e.g. they are SMEs).

column12:
Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

column12:
Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. Set its `.description` according to the definition corresponding to the code in the [EU Main Activity concept-scheme](https://op.europa.eu/en/web/eu-vocabularies/concept-scheme/-/resource?uri=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/main-activity).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

column9: The official name of the organisation.

column9: The organisation's uniform resource locator for exchange of data and documents.

column9: The fax for contacting the organisation. To avoid unnecessary processing of personal data, the fax may allow the identification of a physical person only when necessary (in the sense of the General Data Protection Regulation).

column12:
Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. Set its `.description` according to the definition corresponding to the code in the [EU Main Activity concept-scheme](https://op.europa.eu/en/web/eu-vocabularies/concept-scheme/-/resource?uri=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/main-activity).

If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).

column9: The type of buyer according to procurement legislation (e.g. central government authority, body governed by public law, public undertaking).
column12: Get the Organization object for the buyer, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array. column9: The website where the buyer publishes information regarding procurement procedures (e.g. notices, procurement documents).

column9: The size of the winner, tenderer or subcontractor (e.g. micro enterprise, small enterprise, medium enterprise).

The nationality (or nationalities) of the beneficiary owner(s) of the winner, tenderer, or subcontractor; as published in the register(s) established by anti-money laundering legislation. If such a register does not exist (e.g. in case of non-EU contractors) then equivalent information from other sources.

The nationality (or nationalities) of the beneficiary owner(s) of the winner, tenderer, or subcontractor is not published in the register(s) established by anti-money laundering legislation, because the winner is listed on a regulated market (e.g. a stock exchange) that ensures adequate transparency in line with anti-money laundering legislation.

An identifier of one or more lots. In case of PINs used only for information, the identifier of one or more parts of the notice that may later become lots or a self-standing procedures.  The information in the techniques section refers to this lot (or part) or these lots (or parts).

column9: The mathematical equation or any other description used for complicated weighing of criteria (e.g. non-linear weighing, the analytic hierarchy process) when a weighing cannot be expressed per criterion.

column12: Add an award criterion number to the award criterion's `.numbers` array. Map to its `.number`.

column9: Whether the number linked to an award criterion is a type of weight (e.g. a percentage).

column9: Whether the number linked to an award criterion is a fixed value (e.g. a fixed price, a fixed cost).

column9: An identifier of one or more lots. In case of PINs used only for information, the identifier of one or more parts of the notice that may later become lots or a self-standing procedures. This cancelled or unsuccessful procedure or lot will be relaunched.

An identifier of one or more sections within this notice. The information in the strategic procurement section refers to this section or these sections.

Description of the use of a technical specification, selection criterion, award criterion, or contract performance condition aims to reduce the environmental impacts of the procurement, fulfil social objectives and/or buy an innovative work, supply or service.

Identifier of the field that shall not be immediately published. Only fields concerning the Result value and groups of fields concerning the Tender and Procedure Lot Result can be unpublished. In the case of the sectoral Directive, the award criteria, the procurement procedure, certain dates and in certain cases information about the nature and quantity of a service can be unpublished as well.
The justification for not immediately publishing a field and for the choice of a later date at which it can be published.
The justification for not immediately publishing a field.
The later date at which the originally unpublished field shall be published.

The type of form according to procurement legislation.
column12: Add 'planning' to tag, and set `tender.status` to 'planned'

column9: The European Public Procurement Procedure Identifier, a unique identifier of a procurement procedure. Including this identifier in all published versions of this notice (e.g. published on TED, national publication portals, regional publication portals) allows unique identification of procurement procedures around the EU.
The date and time when the notice has been sent to TED.
column12: Combine the date and time into [a valid date time](https://standard.open-contracting.org/latest/en/schema/reference/?highlight=dates#date), and map to the release's `date`

column9: The European Public Procurement Notice Identifier of this notice. Including this identifier in all published version of this notice (e.g. TED, national publication portals, regional publication portals) allows unique identification of procurement notices around the EU.
column12: Refer to the **guidance for common operations (create a new release)**.

column9: The language(s) in which this notice is officially available. These linguistic versions are equally legally valid.
The preferred date of publication of the notice on TED (e.g. to avoid publication during a national holiday).
The version of the notice. This helps, for example, to avoid errors caused by multiple change notices sent at a similar time.

The information in the previous planning section refers to this lot (or part) or these lots (or parts).

column12: If different from 'combined', map to the lot's `.mainProcurementCategory`. Otherwise, add 'combined' to the lot's `.additionalProcurementCategories` array.

column9: The description of the nature and quantity of what is being bought or of the needs and requirements that should be met in this procedure or lot. In case of a modification notice, the description of the procurement before and after the modification.
The number of units required.

The unit which the good, service, or work comes in, for example hours or kilograms. Where CPV code is a supply which does not need a further unit (e.g. cars), then no unit needs to be given and quantity is taken to be a count, e.g. the "number of cars".
column12: Map to the item's `.unit.id`. column12: [Add a bids statistic](../../operations/#add-a-bids-statistic). Set its `.measure` according to the value of `efbc:StatisticsCode` and to the [submission count types mapping table], and map to its `.value`.

column9: The type of tenders or requests to participate received. The total number of tenders received must be given. When a notice does not fall under Directive 2009/81/EC and is not about social or other specific services, the number of tenders received from micro, small and medium enterprises; the number of tenders received from tenderers registered in other European Economic Area countries and the number of tenders received from tenderers registered in countries outside of the European Economic Area must also be given. All tenders must be counted, regardless of whether they are admissible or inadmissible. For tenders submitted by a group of tenderers (e.g. a consortium), the tender must be counted in the relevant category (e.g. SME) if the majority of the work is expected to be done by tenderers which fall within this category (e.g. they are SMEs).
column12: [Add a bids statistic](../../operations/#add-a-bids-statistic). map to its `.measure` according to the [submission count types mapping table], and set to its `.value` according to the value of `efbc:StatisticsNumeric`.

column9: The date when the contract was concluded. Typically, this is the date when the last contractual party signed the contract. The date of contract conclusion is always later than the end of the standstill period and only once any evidence submitted by the winner has been verified.
The date of the official decision choosing the winning tender.

column12:
Add a new Cascade object to the award's `.cascade` array. Set its `.bid` to the identifier of the corresponding bid. For each related tenderer, add an Organization reference object to the cascade's `.suppliers` array. Copy its `.id` and `.name` from the corresponding Organization object.

The position of the cascade object in the `.cascade` array determines the rank of the bid. Example: `.cascade[0]` should return the highest ranking bid, `.cascade[1]` the second highest ranking bid, etc.

column12: [Add a bids statistic](../../operations/#add-a-bids-statistic). Set its `.measure` according to the value of `efbc:StatisticsCode` and to the [submission count types mapping table], and map to its `.value`.

column9: The type of tenders or requests to participate received. The total number of tenders received must be given. When a notice does not fall under Directive 2009/81/EC and is not about social or other specific services, the number of tenders received from micro, small and medium enterprises; the number of tenders received from tenderers registered in other European Economic Area countries and the number of tenders received from tenderers registered in countries outside of the European Economic Area must also be given. All tenders must be counted, regardless of whether they are admissible or inadmissible. For tenders submitted by a group of tenderers (e.g. a consortium), the tender must be counted in the relevant category (e.g. SME) if the majority of the work is expected to be done by tenderers which fall within this category (e.g. they are SMEs).
column12: [Add a bids statistic](../../operations/#add-a-bids-statistic). map to its `.measure` according to the [submission count types mapping table], and set to its `.value` according to the value of `efbc:StatisticsNumeric`.

column9: The date when the contract was concluded. Typically, this is the date when the last contractual party signed the contract. However, if no contract is signed, then the date of contract conclusion may correspond to other dates (e.g. the date when the buyer notified the winning tenderer). The date of contract conclusion is always later than the end of the standstill period and only once any evidence submitted by the winner has been verified.
The date of the official decision choosing the winning tender.
The uniform resource locator (e.g. the web address) of the contract.
An identifier of the tender or another result that led to this contract.
The name of the contract or, in case of voluntary-ex ante transparency notices and design contest result notices, of the decision.

The name of the European Union funds used to at least partially finance the contract. The most concrete information must be given (e.g. about concrete projects, not just operational programs.)

column12:
Add a new Cascade object to the award's `.cascade` array. Set its `.bid` to the identifier of the corresponding bid. For each related tenderer, add an Organization reference object to the cascade's `.suppliers` array. Copy its `.id` and `.name` from the corresponding Organization object.

The position of the cascade object in the `.cascade` array determines the rank of the bid. Example: `.cascade[0]` should return the highest ranking bid, `.cascade[1]` the second highest ranking bid, etc.

The position of the cascade object in the `.cascade` array determines the rank of the bid. Example: `.cascade[0]` should return the highest ranking bid, `.cascade[1]` the second highest ranking bid, etc.

Get the Organization object, and add a Classification object to its `.details.classifications` array.  Map to its `.id`. If the code is in the [COFOG classification](https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?title=Glossary:Classification_of_the_functions_of_government_\(COFOG\)), set the classification's `.scheme` to ['COFOG'](https://unstats.un.org/unsd/publications/catalogue?selectID=145). Otherwise, set the classification's `.scheme` to ['Directive 2014/25/EU'](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32014L0025#d1e2854-243-1).
